!begin_node Introduction
!html_name intro

"Nobody reads instructions today..."

!begin_center
(!B)HANG ON!(!b) These times have gone, or have they?
!end_center

Whatever the position, clearly the time has come when these
instructions need sprucing up! ST-Guide has become a widely distributed
system in the meantime, has been completely translated into English
(program and docs) and belongs to the standard configuration of many
home and professional Atari system users (pardon me - for some time now
also increasingly on Apples under MagiC MAC!).

Fewer and fewer authors today are willing to forego the inclusion of
online Help in the form of a hypertext with their programs. There are
dictionaries, subject overviews, info-booklets, legal texts and even a
labyrinth game as ST-Guide hypertexts in addition to countless on-line
documentation - in fact anything that can somehow be accommodated in a
hypertext.

!begin_blist
!item [But why hypertext?]

A text document receives a sort of additional dimension as a hypertext:
One can not only 'wander' through it linearly in the conventional
manner, but also jump 'sideways' to other portions of the text. Any
character string in the text can be marked as a cross reference
'pattern' for a link. This allows one to cross-connect related pages,
or simply arrange them in a handy structure.

The advantage: Readers are presented with the text in small chunks with
a clear layout. In particular, if the text has been prepared correctly
one can reach all chapters quickly with a few mouse-clicks or key
presses.

This leaves it up to the user how he/she wants to read the hypertext:
Either each page in turn from the start, or narrowly focussed starting
from a given point.

!item [And now, off we go]!


Here it should be noted that (!B)this(!b) hypertext may be read by browsing
continuously through the pages with the right-facing arrow icon, or
also by using the key-combination (!key [Control - (!RIGHT!)]) ! Although this will not
reach (!B)every(!b) page of this hypertext automatically, it will include all
the important topics. If required, further details can be obtained on
the way with suitable mouse-clicks.

As quite a bit of development has taken place, it is recommended that
even those familiar with earlier versions of ST-Guide should take a
look at this hypertext. It also serves as a demonstration of ST-Guide's
capabilities, such as (!link [graphics] [Lines, arrows and boxes]), for instance.
!end_blist

!raw [stg] @rbox 22 31 3 0
 (!nl)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~Have fun with ST-Guide!!!

!end_node # Introduction


!begin_node The Philosophy of ST-Guide
!alias+ Philosophy
!html_name philosophy

Hypertexts are new. That may not seem to be so when one considers that
they have been available for years, but compared to the traditional
form, books, they offer, besides new options, a new type of
presentation - for which one needs to adopt a different way of working.
In order not to make things unnecessarily difficult, ST-Guide as far as
possible adopts the way that books are structured:

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Main table of contents and perhaps sub tables of contents
!item An alphabetic index
!item The body of text arranged in chapters
!end_itemize

What does this mean in use?

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item One can browse through the text page-by-page forwards and backwards
!item One can jump from each page to the overlying (sub)table of contents
(Contents icon)
!item One can jump from anywhere to the (!INDEX [index])
!item One can set a mark to a page as a bookmark
!item Notes can be included in the form of See also cross references
!item For quick orientation there is a Help page, comparable in a way to
a r‚sum‚ on the (!link [back] [Back icon]) cover of a book.
!end_itemize

!end_node

!begin_node Function overview
!html_name overview

It hardly needs saying that ST-Guide can do more than just 'imitate' a
book. It is a very live system. A collection of interested people are
constantly discussing how ST-Guide can be made even better. The result
of efforts to date is a collection of useful functions that are briefly
outlined here:

!begin_blist
!item [Advantages of using ST-Guide format hypertexts:]

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Comprehensive graphics facilities

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Popup-nodes as alternatives to normal pages
!item Incorporation of graphics, see the Symbol bar page, for instance
!item (!link [Lines, arrows and various box-types] [Lines, arrows and boxes]) (!I)(!link [<-] [Previous page]) Tip: Click here!(!i)
!item Various (!link [text attributes] [Text attributes])
!end_itemize

!item Minimal storage requirements on floppy/hard disks
!item Minimal memory requirements in working RAM
!item Database facilities:

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item The reference files belonging to the hypertexts can be
amalgamated with RefLink into a global index file of all
hypertexts, in which a (!link [REF-find] [Find as REFerence]) can quickly find cross
references to any of the hypertexts
!item The utility STool automatically collects together all available
hypertexts and produces a catalogue from them, using the linking
information contained in the hypertexts
!end_itemize

!item Can be used as a desk accessory as well as a program
!item You can also convert Hypertexts in other formats to ST-Guide format
!item Comprehensive (!link [keyboard] [Keyboard functions]) functions (as an alternative to the mouse)
!item Several find functions, including wildcard support
!item You can branch to Help pages even from normal ASCII texts
!item If GDOS is installed you can select any desired screen font
!item ST-Guide is Fairware, which means that its use is free but
voluntary contributions are requested.
!end_itemize

!item [Benefits is you want to write hypertexts yourself:]

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Easily learned commands syntax
!item Compiler creates cross references to other pages (!I)automatically(!i)!
!item Compiler creates an (!INDEX [index]) (!I)automatically(!i)!
!item All hypertext pages contained in a single, compact file
!item Large variety of design options
!item ST-Guide enables context-sensitive on-line Help to be called
directly from within your programs
!item Original RSC files of programs can be incorporated
!item ST-Guide has now found very wide distribution!
!end_itemize
!end_blist

