!begin_node Floppy and hard disks
!html_name floppy

ST-Guide is very frugal with its mass storage requirements:

!begin_itemize
!item The compiler is able to 'pack' hypertexts, i.e. reduce the amount of
space they occupy on disk. It uses the LH5-algorithm for this, which
also used by the LHARC packer. In this manner hypertext files (with
the extension HYP) can be reduced by up to two-thirds in size. For
displaying the hypertext on the screen the packed pages will be
unpacked again without a perceivable delay.

!item A further space advantage is achieved by the fact that a hypertext is
always saved as a single file: Hypertext systems that create a new
file for every page (e.g. 1st-Guide) have the disadvantage that each
of these files - be it ever so small - always occupies at least one
cluster of your floppy or hard disk, which actually means at least
1024 bytes are consumed (more with large hard disk partitions). If a
hypertext contains many pages whose contents are appreciably smaller
than 1024 bytes or a multiple of this, then the actual room required
on disk rises appreciably because any space up to the end of the
cluster is wasted.
With ST-Guide this problem does not arise, since all the pages are
stored as a single file (moreover in compressed form), so that no
wasteful cluster left-overs are created.
!end_itemize

!end_node # Floppy

!begin_node Working memory
!html_name memory

ST-Guide only makes meager demands on your computer's memory:

!begin_itemize
!item (!file [ST-GUIDE.ACC]) itself is very small, much smaller than other similar
programs with comparable capabilities.

!item Although hypertexts are always saved as a complete file, only a small
part of this is loaded into RAM at any time -- namely only the page
that is to be displayed! Therefore the amount of working memory
occupied by ST-Guide is hardly worth mentioning.
!end_itemize

!end_node

!begin_node Accessory
!html_name accessory

ST-Guide can be started as a desk accessory or a program - the choice
is up to you. If required, simply change the file extension .ACC to
.PRG!

But basically the use as a desk accessory is recommended, specially if
you are not using a multitasking operating system. This way ST-Guide
can also be called up from within other programs, either in its
function as on-line help, or as a universal reference search system for
text editors etc.

!end_node # Accessory

!begin_node ASCII
!raw [stg] @xref "Extra -> Find"
!html_name ascii

Even when the displayed file contains only plain ASCII text, ST-Guide
can branch to other texts.

That works as follows: If you click on a word in the text that you wish
to find a cross-reference to, ST-Guide checks (with a so-called
reference search) whether an explanatory page exists for this
reference, and will display it if found. It is not necessary for the
reference to be specially emphasised, since the search is made for the
character string of the word clicked on (hyphenated words are looked
for as a combination).

If it does not exist then ST-Guide looks for '(!link [similar] [Similar])' character
patterns and displays a list of such references it has found, together
with the name of the text it has found it in. Clicking on one of the
entries will take you straight to the relevant page.

An unsuccessful search will be reported in an appropriate dialogue.

!end_node # ASCII

!end_node # Function overview

!begin_node Configuration
!html_name configuration

How does one adapt ST-Guide to its environment?

All components of ST-Guide can be configured via a file named
ST-GUIDE.INF which has to reside in a folder specified by the HOME
environment variable or in the root directory of the boot
disk/partition (usually C:\ with a hard disk, otherwise A:\).

It is constructed for the most part in a similar way to environment
files of various AUTO folder environment setting programs

Several variables are set in the ST-GUIDE.INF file, some of which
ST-Guide evaluates itself while others are required by external
associated programs. The (!file [ST-GUIDE.INF]) file included in the distribution
already contains a full complement of settings (with comments) and need
not be altered if the ST-Guide archive was unpacked to the root
directory of the C: partition.

ST-GUIDE.INF is a pure ASCII file that can be edited by any ASCII text
editor (e.g. Everest...) if required.

The following environment variables are evaluated by ST-Guide:

!raw [stg] @box 1 12 12 0
!begin_table [ll]
PATHS
(!link [HCP] [HCP])
HYPFIND
HYPFOLD
REF !! Important access paths
REMARKER
EXTVIEW
DEFHYP
HYPTOP
PRINTER
MARKFILE
(!link [<ext>] [<ext>])
!end_table

!raw [stg] @box 1 12 3 0
!begin_table [ll]
TXTCOLOR
REFCOLOR !! Only relevant for colour display
BCK3D
!end_table

!raw [stg] @box 1 12 5 0
!begin_table [ll]
FONT
XFONT
WINSIZE !! Appearance of the ST-Guide window display
TXTOFFSET
TABSIZE
!end_table

!raw [stg] @box 1 12 3 0
!begin_table
RIGHTBACK
REFONLY !! Mouse-behaviour
BACKWIND
!end_table

!raw [stg] @box 1 12 4 0
!begin_table
HCP_OPT
ARROWPATCH !! Miscellaneous
NOREFBOX
$<name>
!end_table


(!B)Example of the construction of a line of this file:(!b)
!begin_verbatim
  ...
  HYPFOLD=C:\GUIDES\
  ...
!end_verbatim

The entire file is line-oriented, and there must be no surplus spaces
in the lines. The syntax is:

!begin_verbatim
  <Variable>=<Value>
!end_verbatim

Note that there may be no spaces before or after the '=', and
<Variable> and <Value> must (!B)not(!b) be enclosed in angle brackets or
quotes.

!begin_node ST-GUIDE.INF
!html_name st_guide_inf

The following environment variables are in use at present:

!begin_blist
!label TABSIZE
!item [TABSIZE]
Sets the desired tabulator width.
A default value of 8 is used unless this value is specified.

!label WINSIZE
!item [WINSIZE]
Contains the size (in pixels) of the ST-Guide window on opening. If
this variable isn't specified the window fills the entire screen.

For example: WINSIZE=40,40,560,360 (!nl)
The first two values (40,40) set the window top left corner. The
next two values (560,360) set the window bottom right corner. In
ST-High (640x400 pixels) the example results in a 520x320 pixel
window positioned centrally on the screen with a 40 pixel border
all round.

Or: WINSIZE=100,100,400,200 (!nl)
This opens a 300x100 pixel ST-Guide window near the centre of a
640x400 pixel screen.

!label TXTOFFSET
!item [TXTOFFSET]
Sets the vertical separation in pixels of the window contents from
the dividing line below the icons. The default value of 6 pixels
will be used if this variable is not specified. This variable
allows one to set a 'top margin' in the hypertexts to suit personal
taste, without the hypertext author having to pre-set it with a
blank line.
(ST-Guide)

!label REFCOLOR
!item [REFCOLOR]
REFCOLOR=<Colour> displays references using the specified <colour>.
If this variable is set, then ST-Guide references are no longer
shown bold and underlined but in normal text in the chosen colour
instead. This variable is ignored in monochrome resolutions.

!label TXTCOLOR
!item [TXTCOLOR]
TXTCOLOR=<Colour> displays the main text using the specified
<colour>. This variable is ignored in monochrome resolutions.

Default colours (Note! Your system may change these values!):

!begin_table [llll]
~0=White      !! ~1=Black      !! ~2=Red         !! ~3=Green
~4=Blue       !! ~5=Cyan       !! ~6=Yellow      !! ~7=Magenta
~8=Grey       !! ~9=Dark grey  !! 10=Dark red    !! 11=Dark green
12=Dark blue  !! 13=Dark cyan  !! 14=Dark yellow !! 15=Dark magenta
!end_table

!label BCK3D
!item [BCK3D]
BCK3D=<the value is immaterial> sets the colour of the window
background to light grey; if this variable is not supplied, then
the ST-Guide window background will be white.

This variable is ignored in monochrome resolutions.

!label PATHS
!item [PATHS]
Contains a list of paths ST-Guide searches to locate files that are
to be displayed via external references (see 'Link' for more
details). Several paths may be entered by seperating each path with
a comma or semi-colon.

For example:

PATHS=c:\guides\;c:\;c:\bin\

will, when a file is being searched for, look successively in (!nl)
(!file [C:\GUIDES\]) (!nl)
(!file [C:\]) (!nl)
and (!nl)
(!file [C:\BIN\]) (!nl)
(ST-Guide, STool)

!label EXTVIEW
!item [EXTVIEW]
Contains the name of the desk accessory or program (ACC/PRG/APP)
used to display non-hypertext files whose file extenders are not
explicitly listed and assigned to a viewer. The full path to the
viewer must be specified unless one can ensure that the
corresponding viewer has already been started. Under single TOS
this means it has been installed as an ACC, in a multi-tasking
environment the viewer can also be a parallel running application.
Additionally viewers for individual file extenders can be
installed.
!label <ext>
Add line/s in the following format:

<Extender>=<Program> (e.g. IMG=C:\1STVIEW\1STVIEW.PRG)

The viewer specified in this way will be searched for when ST-Guide
loads a file with an installed extender, and then either passed to
the desktop for starting, or started by ST-Guide itself as long as
MagiC 2 has been installed.

If this variable does not exist, or the extender of the file to be
displayed does not have a viewer assigned, then the corresponding
file is loaded and displayed by ST-Guide in ASCII format.
(ST-Guide)

!label HCP_OPT
!item [HCP_OPT]
contains the default options for HCP. These are set before the
command line is read in and so can be overwritten by direct input
when calling HCP.
(hcp)

!label PRINTER
!item [PRINTER]
If this variable is set, in the form of

PRINTER=<program> (e.g. PRINTER=C:\TOOLS\PRINTER.APP)

then the printing function will not be carried out by ST-Guide
itself, but the marked block or current page will be copied to the
clipboard, and the program specified here will be started. This may
permit printing in different fonts, line spacings etc.
(ST-Guide)

!label FORMFEED
!item [FORMFEED]
Ensures that a Formfeed is performed after a page has been printed.
(ST-Guide)

!label MARKFILE
!item [MARKFILE]
If this variable is set then ST-Guide automatically loads and saves
any and all marks that are set.
Example: MARKFILE=c:\guides\marks.dat
(ST-Guide)

!label* HCP
!item [HCP]
Contains the complete path to (!file [HCP.TTP]) and is currently used by
STool if its COMPILE option is switched on, as well as the HypFind
utility that outputs its search result to a hypertext.
(STool, HypFind)

!label* HYPFIND
!item [HYPFIND]
Contains the complete path to HypFind, a utility which can search
for any desired mask (string pattern) (!link [in all pages] [Find in all pages]) of one/all
hypertexts. Currently this variable is only used by ST-Guide if the
corresponding button in the '(!link [Find] [Extra -> Find])' dialogue is selected.
(ST-Guide)

!label* REMARKER
!item [REMARKER]
Optionally contains a '!' as well as the complete path of the
Remarker utility; if this variable is defined without the '!', then
ST-Guide will start the utility directly it opens its window;
irrespective of the '!' flag, Remarker will be started by
(!key [Alternate + R]), as long as this variable has been set.

REMARKER=C:\ST-GUIDE\REMARKER.PRG

starts Remarker automatically when opening the ST-Guide window, as
well as with (!key [Alternate + R]).

REMARKER=!C:\ST-GUIDE\REMARKER.PRG

only starts Remarker with (!key [Alternate + R]).
(ST-Guide)

!label HYPFOLD
!item [HYPFOLD]
Contains the default path to the folder containing your hypertexts.
So if no output file is specified for the conversion, HCP will
create new hypertexts in the folder specified by this variable.
ST-Guide also uses this variable to preset the default path when
opening the file selector. HypFind also creates its output file in
this folder.
(ST-Guide, hcp, HypFind)

!label ARROWPATCH
!item [ARROWPATCH]
When this variable is defined (the value is immaterial) and
ST-Guide is started as an ACC in a single-tasking operating system,
this patch corrects an AES bug which prevents the scroll bars in
windowed accessories from working correctly with certain TOS
versions. If you exerience this behaviour:
!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Activate the patch by removing the preceding #. Unless you use
several windowed accessories which also suffer the same problem this
is the simplest solution, but it only fixes ST-Guide itself.
!item A better alternative to this patch is to install the ARROWFIX patch
in your AUTO folder so all your accessories can take advantage of
the fix.
!item Even better, use WINX in your AUTO folder. This utility adds many
desirable features to all GEM windows and removes the problem with
scroll arrows in windowed accessories. Arrowfix and WINX are both
available from BBSs and PD libraries and are naturally included on
the registered user disk!
!item Use MultiTOS which doesn't suffer from this AES bug.
!end_itemize
(ST-Guide)

!label NOREFBOX
!item [NOREFBOX]
Setting this variable (the assigned value is immaterial) prevents
the Find box with the find word in a REF-file, from being
displayed.
(ST-Guide)

!label RIGHTBACK
!item [RIGHTBACK]
If this variable is defined (the value is immaterial), then
pressing the right mouse button will be interpreted in the same way
as a click on the Back icon. This variable is not set as a default,
because:
!begin_itemize !compressed
!item it has the disadvantage that one can no longer perform actions
in background (untopped) windows and
!item right-clicks are handled in different ways by various TOS
versions (source: Martin 'WINX' Osieka)
!end_itemize
(ST-Guide)

!label BACKWIND
!item [BACKWIND]
A right click will make the ST-Guide window in the background
usable by bringing it to the top.
(ST-Guide)

!label REFONLY
!item [REFONLY]
If this variable is defined (the value is immaterial), then clicks
on words not emphasised as cross-references will be ignored.
(ST-Guide)

!label DEFHYP
!item [DEFHYP]
Contains the complete default path and filename of the hypertext
automatically loaded by ST-Guide if called (!U)without parameters(!u),
typically ST-GUIDE.HYP (or HCP).
(ST-Guide)

!label HYPTOP
!item [HYPTOP]
Contains the complete path and filename for the CATALOG hypertext
which can be automatically created using STool. ST-Guide
automatically loads this file if no parameters are passed and no
default hypertext has been specified in DEFHYP.
(ST-Guide, STooL)

!label FONT
!item [FONT]
Contains the font and point size to be used in the following
format: FONT,SIZE

For example: 98,9 (GEMINI bold, small character set)

ST-Guide loads this variable as it opens the window, so any
available font can be selected any time before a window is opened,
though it's currently not possible to change the font while an
ST-Guide window is open.

If FONT is given as 0 (e.g.: 0,9) then the system character set in
the given size is used.

In principle proportional character sets can be used, but because
calculations for graphical objects (images, icons, lines etc) are
made based on the average character width, pages which combine text
and graphics may not look their best!
(ST-Guide)

!label XFONT
!item [XFONT]
Contains the font and point size to be used in the following
format: FONT,SIZE
Definition of 2 default fonts; this enables the user to switch
between FONT and XFONT by using (!key [Control + Z]). Useful when you want
to read with a proportional font, but come across a page with a
table in it.

!label REF
!item [REF]
Contains the path and filename of the REF file used by ST-Guide to
find cross references which haven't been defined in the current
hypertext. This file is also used as the default by RefLink for all
of its functions.
(ST-Guide, RefLink, hcp)

!label $<name>
!item [$<name>]
Can be repeated a number of times (naturally with different names)
and contains in each case the complete path to an external program
that can then be started from within hypertexts with the (!XLINK [@{ system }] [hcp] [@{ system }])
command. Example:

$STOOL=c:\st-guide\stool.tos

Those writing hypertexts making use of this function have to
provide information about which $-lines are required.
(ST-Guide)
!end_blist

