!begin_node Back icon
!html_name back_hv

!stg_limage [off]
!image (!IMAGES)stg_back
!stg_limage [on]
!begin_xlist [~~~~~~]
!item [~~~~~~] ST-Guide remembers in which order one has called up which pages,
by storing them on a stack that may hold up to sixteen pages.

With the Back icon one can browse back through the pages in
reverse order, thus more or less reversing one's steps in
reaching the current page. Naturally this only works when there
are some pages on the stack, which is not the case when ST-Guide
is first opened, for instance. One can erase the stack, if
desired, at the press of a mouse button. This function can also
be carried out with the (!key [Esc]) or (!key [Undo]) keys, as well as with
the right mouse button (if RIGHTBACK is set).

If one wants to jump back (!B)several(!b) pages at once, the one can use
the adjacent icon to bring up the History popup.
!end_xlist

!end_node

!begin_node History popup
!html_name historypop_hv

!stg_limage [off]
!image (!IMAGES)stg_hist
!stg_limage [on]
!begin_xlist [~~~~~~]
!item [~~~~~~] Clicking on this icon allows one to jump (!link [back] [Back icon]) several pages. The
last 12 stack entries will be displayed in the form of a
History- popup, with the page read last at the top and the one
read first at the bottom. Clicking on one of the entries with
the mouse immediately opens the relevant page. The phrase in the
popup may not be longer than forty characters! Anything beyond
this will be cut off.

The icon is not selectable (greyed out) if there are no
hypertext pages on the stack. This will be the case when
ST-Guide is first opened, and after using the (!link [Erase stack] [Extra -> Erase stack])
function.

The suspicion that selecting the first entry in this popup has
the same effect as using the Back icon is correct! (The
relationship of the effects of these two icons is therefore
illustrated by the use of a thinner dividing line between them.)
The Back icon merely permits faster access to the page read
(!B)last(!b).
!end_xlist

!end_node

