!begin_node Find in page
!html_name find_inpage_hv

All lines from the first visible line to the end of the current page
are searched for matches to the string input as the search pattern.
If a match is found, the text scrolls so that the line containing
the match is the first to be visible in the window. This search is
(!link [case insensitive] [insens]) and can be repeated using the (!link [Repeat find] [Extra -> Repeat find]) option.

!begin_pnode insens
!html_name insens_hv
'case insensitive' means that
capital and lower case characters
are treated as equivalent.
Therefore 'TEST', 'test' and 'Test'
will be treated as identical patterns.
!end_node

!end_node # Find in page

!begin_node Find as page
!html_name find_aspage_hv

This searches the current hypertext's index for the search pattern
that was input. Wildcards may be used, and the search is
(!link [case insensitive] [insens]).
!alias+ Hitlist
If more than one match is found a dialogue appears listing all
matching index entries. Select the desired entry using the mouse or
(!link [keyboard] [Keyboard functions]) shortcut. In this dialogue one line is always highlighted,
and the following shortcuts are available:

!begin_xlist [Shift + Curs.down] !compressed
!item [Return]             Selects the line
!item [Cursor up]          Selects the previous line
!item [Cursor down]        Selects the next line
!item [Undo]               Same as the (!link [Cancel] [Cancel]) button
!item [Shift + Curs.up]    Displays the previous page in list
!item [Shift + Curs.down]  Displays the next page in list
!item [ClrHome]            Displays the first page in list
!item [Shift + ClrHome]    Displays the last page in list
!end_xlist

Naturally the sliders and other functions work like you'd expect in
any GEM window.

The hitlist line contains the name of the page along with the theme
of the corresponding hypertext. If a match to a cross-reference
within a page is found, then this will be displayed after the page
name as well, separated by a 'bullet' dot.

!label- Similar
!index Similar
If no exact match is found, references that are similar will be
presented for selection. 'Similar' here is defined as follows:

!begin_itemize !compressed
!item Upper and lower case differences are ignored
!item '„' is treated the same as 'ae', '' as 'ue' etc.
!item '*' fits any number of characters, even none
!item '?' fits exactly one character
!item Depending on the length of the word a few characters are allowed
to differ. For example 'option' and 'optoin' will be treated as a
match.
!end_itemize

!begin_pnode Cancel
!html_name cancel_hv
This button quits the dialogue
without starting a search.
!end_node

!end_node # Find as page

!begin_node Find as REFerence
!label REF-find
!html_name find_asref_hv

The input string pattern will be searched for in the file specified
in the REF variable; apart from this the search is identical to
Find as page.

To express this more clearly: This search method deals with
searching for a cross-reference or a character string in the global
reference file specified in ST-GUIDE.INF with the REF variable
(usually ALL.REF) which has been produced by the RefLink utility
that combines the cross- reference files of individual hypertexts
into a master file. Thus the search is not confined to just one
hypertext, but extended to the cross-references of all hypertexts
that have been processed by RefLink.

This search method is useful, for instance, if one selects a word
in a correspondingly equipped text editor and then activates the
Help function. If a hypertext page corresponding to the searched
for word or character string (which may contain several words)
exists somewhere, then ST-Guide will find this page and display it.

!end_node # Find as REFerence

!begin_node Find in all pages
!html_name find_allpages_hv

This utilises the external ST-Guide utility HypFind included in the
ST-Guide distribution. The environment variable HYPFIND must be
defined in ST-GUIDE.INF.

The search is case insensitive and the utility produces a hit list
of all all matching entries in the form of a hypertext that will be
loaded automatically by ST-Guide when HypFind terminates. So that
HypFind can be called, one has to either;
!begin_itemize !compressed
!item install MagiC, in which case ST-Guide starts the utility itself,
or
!item use an AV-desktop, such as Thing or Gemini for instance (it may
also work with Ease), in which case ST-Guide instructs the desktop
to start HypFind.
!end_itemize

Users for whom neither of the above conditions apply can only start
HypFind manually and use its command line.

!end_node # Find in all pages

!end_node # Extra -> Find

!begin_node Extra -> Repeat find
!raw [stg] @xref "Extra -> Find"
!alias+ Repeat find
!index Repeat find
!html_name find_repeat_hv

With this function the current page is searched again for the search
pattern last input, but the search starts from the second visible line
in the window so that one does not have to scroll first before one can
continue the search.

The key combination for this function is (!key [Control + G]).

!end_node # Repeat Find

!begin_node Extra -> Erase stack
!alias Erase stack
!html_name clearstack_hv

This function erases the stack in which the pages that one can reach
with 'Back' are stored. Alternatively one can also press the key
combination (!key [Alternate + E]).

This action deactivates both the Back icon and the History popup.

!end_node

!begin_node Extra -> Copy
!raw [stg] @xref "Extra -> Paste"
!alias Copy
!index Copy
!html_name extra_copy_hv

This function (or the key-code (!key [Control + C])) writes the current page
as an ASCII-text (i.e. without attributes or cross-references) into the
clipboard and thus makes it available to other GEM applications. If no
clipboard exists as yet then one will be created, as usual as a folder
CLIPBRD on the boot drive.

If during this action one of the (!key [Shift])-keys is held down, then any
previous clipboard contents will not be overwritten, but the new text
will be appended to the existing one.

!end_node

!begin_node Extra -> Paste
!raw [stg] @xref "Extra -> Copy"
!alias+ Paste
!index Paste
!html_name extra_paste_hv

Clicking on this entry, or pressing (!key [Control + V]) causes ST-Guide to
load the file SCRAP.TXT from the clipboard, if it can, and then display
it in the window.

!end_node

!begin_node Extra -> Print page
!alias+ Print page
!index Print
!html_name extra_print_hv

This function (also available with the key-combination (!key [Control + P]))
does exactly what one would expect from it, namely output the current
page as ASCII text to the printer.

The notorious 'Atari-ž' will be converted by ST-Guide automatically to
the 'correct ž' during this, so that all the German Umlaut characters
should appear correctly in the printout.

Alternatively there is the option of defining the variable PRINTER in
the ST-GUIDE.INF file. In that case, instead of printing directly when
the 'Print' function is called, the program specified in the variable
will be started and the contents of the page to be printed will be
copied to the clipboard from where they can be read by the external
program. This diversion also works in the (!link [Block popup] [Mouse functions])16}.

As may have already become clear, one can thus use the 'Print' function
to call an external printing program (that may allow selection of
fonts, line-spacing etc.) on the one hand, and on the other hand to
also use it for other purposes such as calling an editor or similar
program, for instance.

!end_node

!begin_node Extra -> Font
!alias+ Font
!html_name extra_font_hv

ST-Guide supports the so-called font-protocol by Christian Grunenberg,
for which the environment variable FONTSELECT is evaluated. If it is
possible to call up a font selector in this way, then one can select
any desired font via this entry of the Extra popup for ST-Guide to use
for displaying text in its window.

If no font selector is installed then a corresponding message appears,
and if no GDOS or equivalent has been installed then only the system
font can be used for display.

(!B)Note:(!b) Most available hypertexts assume that a monospaced font, i.e. a
non-proportional type, is in use. Hence it is strongly recommended that
one should basically work with such monospaced fonts to prevent gross
distortions in the appearance of the pages, particularly those using
the graphical commands.

The key-combination for this function is (!key [Alternate + Y]) (on English, US
and similar keyboards; German keyboards use (!key [Alternate + Z]).)

!end_node


!begin_node Extra -> Remarker
!raw [stg] @xref "remarker.hyp/Main" "Notepads-Tool REMARKER"
!index Remarker
!html_name extra_remarker_hv

!stg_limage [off]
!image (!IMAGES)stg_rem
!stg_limage [on]
!begin_xlist [~~~~~~] !compressed
!item [~~~~~~] The REMARKER, written by Christoph Spengler, is a companion
program to ST-Guide that allows annotations for given hypertext
pages to be created, stored and recalled again at any time very
simply. ST-Guide is well prepared for cooperation with Remarker.

If the variable REMARKER is defined in ST-GUIDE.INF, or Remarker
is also running, then this menu entry can be selected in the
Extra popup or activated by the key-combination (!key [Alternate + R]).
ST-Guide then calls or starts the Remarker. If REMARKER is
already in memory, ST-Guide will show this by displaying the
'Notes' icon at the far right of the icon-bar.

One can deduce two things from the appearance of the
REMARKER-icon:

!begin_enumerate
!item If it is visible, then it means that the Remarker is already
present in memory.
!item The icon can take also take one of two possible forms: It can
be drawn greyed out or in black. The latter indicates that
one or more notes exist for the currently displayed hypertext
page.

(!B)Attention:(!b) The Remarker-icon is also selectable when it is in
its greyed out form! In this it differs from the other icons,
but due to this one can access the Remarker faster when one
wishes to input notes. People who find this 'inconsistent'
can of course continue using menu selection from the (!link [Extra] [Extra popup])
popup.
!end_enumerate

After being called the REMARKER thus opens its window and
displays any notes that may be present. If there are none the
notes window is empty, of course, but new notes may be entered
from the keyboard. Further details are given in the Remarker
documentation.

(!B)Note(!b): The REMARKER is a Shareware program.

!end_xlist

!end_node

!end_node # Extra popup

!end_node # The icons in the ST-Guide window

!begin_node Mouse functions
!raw [stg] @xref "Symbol bar" "Icon bar"
!raw [stg] @xref "Keyboard functions"
!raw [stg] @xref "Auto locator"
!html_name mouse_hv

Mouse operation has been kept very simple. A single click with the left
mouse button is all that is needed in virtually any case. This applies
both to the icons as well as clicking on text in the window.

(!B)Note:(!b) You can click not just on words or phrases emphasised as cross
references, but also on unmarked words as long as the REFONLY variable
has not been set in ST-GUIDE.INF. ST-Guide will then find the Reflink
generated global cross reference index file (REF) for the word clicked
on, and display the corresponding page if the find was successful.


In a few exceptional cases, mouse operation needs something different
from a simple left-click:
!alias+ Block popup

!begin_itemize
!item Holding down the left mouse button marks the line the cursor is
resting on as a block, which can be extended downwards by dragging
the mouse. After releasing the button a popup appears in which you
can choose to copy the marked block to the clipboard or print the
block.

!item The right mouse button can be used as an alternative to the Back
icon if the RIGHTBACK variable has been defined in ST-GUIDE.INF and
the click is made when the mouse cursor is inside the ST-Guide
window. This function is not fully 'blessed' by the operating
system, so to speak, and is therefore not activated at first. Mouse
fetishists may however see an advantage in the fast jump-(!link [back] [Back icon])
facility, and it is for them that this function has been
implemented.
!end_itemize

!end_node # Mouse functions

!begin_node Keyboard functions
!raw [stg] @xref "Symbol bar" "Icon bar"
!raw [stg] @xref "Mouse functions"
!raw [stg] @xref "Auto locator"
#!label* Keyboard
!html_name keyboard_hv

ST-Guide can be operated almost completely from the keyboard. The
control functions are implemented from, or together with, non
alphanumeric keys. If alphanumeric characters are input, on the other
hand, then the auto- locator springs into action.


(!B)Here follow the defined keyboard shortcuts:(!b)

!begin_table [ll]
Cursor keys                 !! Scroll one line or column
                            !! (like scroll arrows in a window)
Shift + Cursor keys         !! Scroll one page (like clicks
                            !! under/over/next to sliders)
Number pad - or
Ctrl + Cursor up/left       !! Turn to previous page
Number pad + or
Ctrl + Cursor down/right    !! Turn to next page (like icon [(!link [->] [Next page])])
Escape or Undo              !! To last page displayed (like Back icon)
ClrHome                     !! To start of current page (like dragging
                            !! slider right to the top)
Shift + ClrHome             !! To end of current page (like dragging
                            !! slider right to the bottom)
Tab                         !! Sets mark to the next reference
                            !! (cycling through visible portion of
                            !! window only)
Shift + Tab                 !! Sets mark to the previous reference
                            !! cycling through visible portion of
                            !! window only)
Return or Enter             !! Display marked reference
Alternate + T               !! Display contents page (like (!link [Contents] [Contents icon])
                            !! icon)
Alternate + X               !! Display index page (like Index icon)

Control + I                 !! Program information (like (!link [Info Dialogue] [Info icon]))
Help                        !! Displays Help page of the current text
                            !! (like Help icon)
Alternate + K               !! Load Catalogue
Alternate + D               !! Load DEFHYP
Alternate + R               !! Open Remarker if this is running or if
                            !! the variable REMARKER is defined
Control + O                 !! Load file (like (!link [Load icon] [Load file]))
Shift + Control + O         !! Like Control + O , but with *.* preset
                            !! as mask in file selector that appears
Control + F                 !! Find character string pattern (like
                              Extra -> Find)
Control + G                 !! Find next occurrence of string pattern
Alternate + E               !! (!link [Erase stack] [Extra -> Erase stack]) (like Extra -> Erase stack)
Control + C                 !! (!link [Copy] [Extra -> Copy]) current page to clipboard (like
                              Extra -> Copy)
Control + V                 !! Load contents of clipboard into window
                              (like (!link [Extra -> Paste] [Extra -> Paste]))
Control + P                 !! Print current page (like (!link [Extra -> Print page] [Extra -> Print page]))
Control + U                 !! Close Window (like clicking on Closer symbol in window)
                            !! Quits ST-Guide if this was the last open window
Control + Q                 !! Quit ST-Guide
F1 .. F10                   !! Call bookmarks 1 to 10
Shift - F1 .. Shift - F10   !! Define bookmarks 1 to 10
!end_table

!end_node # Keyboard functions

!begin_node Auto locator
!raw [stg] @xref "Symbol bar" "Icon bar"
!raw [stg] @xref "Keyboard functions"
!raw [stg] @xref "Mouse functions"
!html_name autoloc_hv

If characters of any kind are input without non alphanumeric keys (such
as (!key [Control]), (!key [Alternate]) etc) being pressed at the same time, then
ST-Guide interprets the input as a character string 'pattern' to be
searched for. In that case the icon-bar vanishes temporarily and a text
field appears showing the string that has been input; this may be
edited.

For each character input an immediate attempt will be made to find the
complete character string (!link [case insensitive] [insens]) in the current page; if found,
the display scrolls automatically to the corresponding line. This
search is a pure text search and so does not differentiate between
marked cross references and 'plain' text. If the found string is a
cross reference then pressing the (!key [Tab]) key (followed by (!key [Return])) or a
mouse click will suffice to bring this up on the screen.

With the (!key [Insert]) key one can repeat the search for the same string
pattern in the rest of the page. The (!key [Backspace]) key deletes the typed
string one character at a time backwards, while additionally pressing
the Shift key the clears the complete line at once.

The (!link [Icon bar] [Symbol bar]) will re-appear immediately when any window scrolling is
initiated with the cursor keys or the mouse, so that the auto-locator
text area will be covered until it is activated anew. The input string
pattern will remain, however, and will reappear with further auto
locator input. Changing to another hypertext page will however delete
it.

!end_node # Auto locator

!end_node # Using ST-Guide

!begin_node ST-Guide and its environment
!html_name environment_hv

!begin_node Hypertexts in other formats
!html_name other_hv

!begin_blist
!item [1stGuide]

An alternative hypertext system called 1stGuide by Guido Vollbeding has
been available for some time.

In order to simplify the change-over to ST-Guide (to save storage space
on floppy/hard disk, for instance) a conversion program called (!link [1stConv] [Converter])
is provided. This makes it relatively painless to convert 1st Guide
hyper- texts into ST-Guide format.

Since 1stGuide also follows the AV- and PureC-Help protocols, it can
simply be replaced by ST-Guide.

@line 20 35 0 0 7

!item [PureC-Help]

To make the transition to ST-Guide easier, it's been made fully
compatible to the PureC-HelpACC, at least as far as the messages are
concerned. This means that ST-Guide understands all the messages that
can also be evaluated by the PureC-ACC and replies to them in the
corresponding manner.

Any programs which support the PureC-ACC should work happily with
ST-Guide. Simply rename ST-GUIDE to "PC_HELP.ACC" so calling programs
can recognise it as such and access it.

Programmers should find the (!link [List of messages] [The PureC-Help protocol]) of interest.

A conversion program for converting PureC Help-texts to the ST-Guide
format is now part of the system and is called (!link [PC-Conv] [Converter]).

!end_blist

!begin_node The PureC-Help protocol
!alias+ PureC-protocol
!html_name purec_hv
!index PureC-protocol

The basic construction of such a message is:
!begin_table [lll]
buffer[0] = !! <Message-type>                   !! (e.g. AC_HELP)
buffer[1] = !! <Sender ID>                      !! (from appl_init())
buffer[2] = !! <Version number>                 !! (for AC_REPLY)
            !! 0                                !! (all others)
buffer[3] = !! Pointer to search pattern (High) !! (for AC_HELP)
            !! <Handle of the ACC-window>       !! (for AC_REPLY)
            !! 0                                !! (all others)
buffer[4] = !! Pointer to search pattern (Low)  !! (for AC_HELP)
            !! 0                                !! (all others)
buffer[5] = !! 0x1993                           !! (poss. for AC_HELP)
            !! 0                                !! (all others)
buffer[6] = !! Pointer to Index file (High)     !! (if AC_HELP & 0x1993)
            !! 0                                !! (otherwise)
buffer[7] = !! Pointer to Index file (Low)      !! (if AC_HELP & 0x1993)
            !! 0                                !! (otherwise)
!end_table

!begin_blist [AC_VERSION]
!label AC_HELP
!item [AC_HELP] (1025)
(!U)APP -> ACC(!u): 'Show the Info for the reference given'.

(!U)ACC -> APP(!u): AC_REPLY (see there), after the matching file has been
searched for and the desired page displayed, or the search broken
off if unsuccessful.

The search for the reference is made in the file specified either
in 'REF' or in the message. Similar string patterns will also be
found.

!label AC_REPLY
!item [AC_REPLY] (1026)
(!U)ACC -> APP(!u): Reply to all messages.

!label AC_VERSION
!item [AC_VERSION] (1027)
(!U)APP -> ACC(!u): 'Tell me your version number'. (!nl)
(!U)ACC -> APP(!u): AC_REPLY (see there).

!label AC_COPY
!item [AC_COPY] (1028)
(!U)APP -> ACC(!u): 'Write the current page to the clipboard'. (!nl)
(!U)ACC -> APP(!u): AC_REPLY (see there), after the current page
has been written as ASCII text (SCRAP.TXT) into the clipboard.
!end_blist

!end_node # PureC-protocol

!end_node # Hypertexts in other formats

!begin_node ST-Guide and the AV-protocol
!html_name avprot_hv
!alias AV-protocol

The AV-protocol, which originated from the alternative desktop GEMINI,
enjoys widespread support, so it seemed sensible to support it.

Programmers should find the list of messages of interest.

The basic construction of such a message is:

!begin_table [lll]
buffer[0] = !! <Message-type>              (e.g. VA_START)
buffer[1] = !! <Sender-ID>                 (from appl_init())
buffer[2] = !! 0                           ('overlength')
buffer[3] = !! <Control-keys>              (SENDKEY)
            !! <Window-handle>             (ACCWINDOPEN)
            !! <Window-handle>             (ACCWINDCLOSED)
            !! <Window-handle>             (DRAGACCWIND)
            !! Pointer to path (High)      (STARTPROG)
buffer[4] = !! <Pressed key>               (SENDKEY)
            !! Pointer to path (Low)       (STARTPROG)
            !! <Mouse X-Pos.>              (DRAGACCWIND)
            !! 0                           (all others)
buffer[5] = !! <Pointer to line> (High)    (STARTPROG)
            !! <Mouse Y-Pos.>              (DRAGACCWIND)
            !! 0                           (all others)
buffer[6] = !! <Pointer to line> (Low)     (STARTPROG)
            !! <Pointer to path> (High)    (DRAGACCWIND)
            !! 0                           (all others)
buffer[7] = !! <Pointer to path> (Low)     (DRAGACCWIND)
            !! 0                           (all others)
!end_table

The following messages are recognised/used:

!begin_blist [AV_ACCWINDCLOSED]

!label VA_START
!item [VA_START]: (0x4711)
(!U)APP -> ACC(!u): 'Wake up and start work'; (!nl)
(!U)ACC -> APP(!u): Perhaps AV_ACCWINDOPEN, after the window has opened
and any selected file has been loaded. If a command line has been
input and contains more than one argument, then everything starting
from the first space is interpreted as the name of the page to be
displayed.

According to the AV-documentation all file names must be input in
capitals with complete paths. In order to comply with this whilst
bearing in mind the called application doesn't know where the
hypertext is, the special case of 'drive *' has been implemented:
'*:\AES.HYP' instructs ST-Guide to search for AES.HYP in all known
paths.

A call using 'C:\AES.HYP appl_init' loads AES.HYP and displays the
<appl_init> page from it.

A call using 'C:\AES.REF appl_init' would search for the reference
<appl_init> in the file AES.REF, and if successful would load the
file AES.HYP and display that page from it in which the reference
searched for was defined.

A call using 'C:\AES.HYP' loads the selected file and displays the
first page from it.

A call using 'appl_init' searches for a matching reference in the
file assigned to the REF variable in ST-GUIDE.INF (usually
ALL.REF). If a matching reference is found the appropriate
hypertext is loaded and displayed at the appropriate page.


!label VA_DRAGACCWIND
!item [VA_DRAGACCWIND]: (0x4725)
APP -> ACC: 'A file has been dragged to one of your windows, here's
the path'. Following this ST-Guide loads the file and displays it
in the window. The complete path/filename must be given.

!label AV_SENDKEY
!item [AV_SENDKEY]: (0x4710)
ACC -> APP: 'A key has been pressed which I can't do anything with,
so you can have it'. This makes it possible to use the keyboard
shortcuts in an application even if an accessory is the topped
window.

!label AV_STARTPROG
!item [AV_STARTPROG]: (0x4723)
ACC -> APP: 'Start up the program specified in this message with
the (possibly) specified command line'. ST-Guide uses this message
to execute SYSTEM instructions. With Thing and GEMINI you can also
specify non-executable files and if a program is installed for the
given extension it will be started and the file loaded.

APP -> ACC: VA_PROGSTART, which will however be ignored by ST-Guide.

!label AV_ACCWINDOPEN
!item [AV_ACCWINDOPEN]: (0x4724)
ACC -> APP: 'I've just opened a window'. Since the window's handle
is also passed, this serves the purpose, among others, to extend
window cycling of the main application to the windows of the ACC,
or to report to the ACC when objects have been dragged to one of
its windows (see VA_DRAGACCWIND).

!label AV_ACCWINDCLOSED
!item [AV_ACCWINDCLOSED]: (0x4726)
ACC -> APP: 'I've just closed one of my windows'. Counterpart to
ACCWINDOPEN.

!label AV_EXIT
!item [AV_EXIT]:
ACC -> APP: 'I'm closing down - and goodbye'

!label AV_PROTOKOLL
!item [AV_PROTOKOLL]:
ACC -> APP: 'I'm here'

!end_blist

!end_node # ST-Guide and the AV-protocol

!end_node # ST-Guide and its environment

